### Description

[dump](https://aupctf.s3.eu-north-1.amazonaws.com/dump.txt)

**Flag format:`aupCTF{***_*****}`**

### Approach

the dump file contains a very large base64 string

```bash

```

lets decode it

```bash
┌──(kali㉿iasad)-[~/CTFs/aupctf]
└─$ cat dump.txt | base64 -d > data

┌──(kali㉿iasad)-[~/CTFs/aupctf]
└─$ file data
data: JPEG image data, JFIF standard 1.01

┌──(kali㉿iasad)-[~/CTFs/aupctf]
└─$ mv data photo.jpeg
```

When the photo is revealed, we encounter a famous dialogue from Game of Thrones. Syrio Forel asks Arya Stark, "What do we say to the god of death?" Arya replies, "Not today.”

## **Masterpeice (100pts)**

### Description

chahat has something for you listen carefully till the end.

[masterpiece.wav](https://aupctf.s3.eu-north-1.amazonaws.com/masterpiece.wav)

### Approach

the first thing I do with audio steganography is to look for [Spectrogram](https://www.wikiwand.com/en/Spectrogram). you can use [sonic-visualiser](https://www.sonicvisualiser.org/) to do this.

Open the file "masterpiece.wav" using sonic-visualiser and navigate to the "Layer" section. and add Spectrogram layer, scroll to the end and you will get the flag

## **LSB (100pts)**

### Description

you got this...[file](https://aupctf.s3.eu-north-1.amazonaws.com/naruto.png)

### Approach

its clear from the name of the challenge that flag is hidden in least significant bits we can use zsteg to extract the flag

```bash
┌──(kali㉿iasad)-[~/CTFs/aupctf]
└─$ zsteg naruto.png
imagedata           .. text: "$:;`VV(-1"
b1,b,lsb,xy         .. file: OpenPGP Secret Key
b1,rgb,lsb,xy       .. text: "aupCTF{zst1g-1s-c00l_rig3ht}"
b2,rgb,lsb,xy       .. file: big endian ispell 3.0 hash file
```

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

---

**Flag: `aupCTF{zst1g-1s-c00l_rig3ht}`**

## **Deep (200pts)**

### Description

[truefan.wav](https://aupctf.s3.eu-north-1.amazonaws.com/truefan.wav)

**Flag format: `aupCTF{****_****}`**

**Hint💡: looking for password ? well thats the iconic dialogue of iron man**

### Approach

its a very large audio file and we know an audio stego tool that can hide very large data in audio files and the name of the challenge also hint to that its **deepsound**

Upon opening the file using DeepSound, we successfully uncover the hidden data, which happens to be password-protected. Following the provided hint, we enter "iamironman" as the password, and indeed, it is the currect password.

We have obtained an executable file named "marvel.exe." you have two options: either decompile the file or answer a series of questions to obtain the flag.

As a marvel fan I can answer the question

![image](/write-ups/aupctf/stego/3.webp#center)

Now that we have the flag format, we know that Iron Man made his first appearance in 2008 and his last appearance in 2019. Therefore, the flag is "aupCTF{2008_2019}".

## **Obfuscated (200pts)**

### Description

[download file](https://aupctf.s3.eu-north-1.amazonaws.com/flag.jpg)

### Approach

we have a broken image lets compare its magic bytes with a real jpeg image

**Given File Header: `FF 8D FF 0E 00 01 A4 64 94 64 00 10`
Real JPEG Header:  `FF D8 FF E0 00 10 4A 46 49 46 00 01`**

we can see that the every two hexadecimals have been swapped with each other in the whole image, we can fix it using python 

```bash
def reverse_hex_swap_in_jpg(file_path):
    with open(file_path, 'rb') as file:
        data = file.read()

    hex_data = data.hex()

    reversed_hex_data = ''.join([hex_data[i+1] + hex_data[i] for i in range(0, len(hex_data), 2)])
    reversed_data = bytes.fromhex(reversed_hex_data)

    new_file_path = recovered + '.jpg'
    with open(new_file_path, 'wb') as new_file:
        new_file.write(reversed_data)

    print(f"Hex values reversed successfully. JPG saved as '{new_file_path}'.")

jpg_file_path = 'flag.jpg'
reverse_hex_swap_in_jpg(jpg_file_path)
```

## **XOR (300pts)**

### Description

### Approach

Two noise images are provided for the challenge, and the task name implies that we need to perform an XOR operation on the two images. This can be accomplished using either a Python script or the stegsolve.jar tool.

Here is a Python script that can perform the required XOR operation:

```python
from PIL import Image

img1 = Image.open("img1.png")
img2 = Image.open("img2.png")

original_image = Image.new("RGB", img1.size)

for x in range(img1.width):
    for y in range(img1.height):
        pixel_img1 = img1.getpixel((x, y))
        pixel_img2 = img2.getpixel((x, y))

        original_pixel = tuple(p1 ^ p2 for p1, p2 in zip(pixel_img1, pixel_img2))
        original_image.putpixel((x, y), original_pixel)

original_image.save("recovered.png")
```

Another approach is to use stegsolve.jar:

1. Open **`img1`** using stegsolve.jar.
2. Go to the "Analyze" tab and select "Image Combiner." and add `**img2**`

  

![image](/write-ups/aupctf/stego/5.webp#center)

**Resultant Image**

![image](/write-ups/aupctf/stego/6.webp#center)

It appears that we have YouTube Shorts ID "LYkCU8Kn3a8." To verify its contents, we can visit the URL **https://www.youtube.com/shorts/LYkCU8Kn3a8**.

Upon visiting the page, we find that the video displays random color hues. The description of the video hints that it may be a cipher. A simple Google search reveals that it is indeed a Hexahue cipher.

To decode the cipher, we can use the following online tool: **https://www.dcode.fr/hexahue-cipher**.

![image](/write-ups/aupctf/stego/7.webp#center)

After decoding the Hexahue cipher using the provided website, we successfully obtained our flag.

## **Arcane (300pts)**

### Description

### Approach

Given is an archive file with a `.exe` extension. When executed, it generates a directory containing 1000 images of Jinx, along with an `img` file.

The img file appears to be corrupted. Upon examining its hex code, it is confirmed that it is a PNG file with a corrupted magic header. To fix this issue, we need to repair the magic header and then open the image. you can find the correct magic header for PNG [here](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_file_signatures)

![image](/write-ups/aupctf/stego/8.webp#center)

After repairing the image and opening it, we find that it is as a plain white image. To further investigate and extract any hidden data, we can utilize a tool called stegsolve.jar. This tool enables us to analyze and extract hidden information from images.

**Blue plane 3** gives us this: a hint

![image](/write-ups/aupctf/stego/9.webp#center)

The given hint suggests that the password to unlock the flag is the name of the character, which is "jinx". To extract hidden data from JPEG images, we can utilize a tool called steghide. However, manually applying steghide to all 1000 images is impractical. To automate the process, we can use a bash one-liner.

```bash
┌──(kali㉿iasad)-[~/CTFs/aupctf]
└─$ ls | while read line; do steghide extract -sf $line -p "jinx"; done
------------MORE----------------
steghide: could not extract any data with that passphrase!
steghide: could not extract any data with that passphrase!
steghide: could not extract any data with that passphrase!
steghide: could not extract any data with that passphrase!
steghide: could not extract any data with that passphrase!
wrote extracted data to "flag.txt".

┌──(kali㉿iasad)-[~/CTFs/aupctf]
└─$ cat flag.txt            
aupCTF{JinxTheArcaneTrickster}
```
